revision.text: ==English== ===Etymology=== From {{inh|en|enm|*yenen}}, {{m|enm|ȝenen}}, {{m|enm|eanen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|*ġeēanian}}, {{m|ang|ēanian||to yean, bring forth young (usually lambs), bring forth as a ewe}} (for the prefixed form, compare {{cog|ang|ġeēan}}, {{m|ang|ġeēane||yeaning|pos=adjective}}), from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*gaaunōn}}, {{m|gmw-pro|*aunōn||to yean, lamb}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*aunōną||to yean, lamb}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂egʷnós||lamb}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|yean||to yean}}, {{cog|stq|bejänne||to produce; show signs of calving}}, {{cog|fy|antsje}}, {{m|fy|eandsje}}, {{m|fy|inje||to yean}}, {{cog|nl|onen||to yean}}, {{cog|sv|öna||to yean|pos=dialectal}}. Akin also to Latin {{m|la|agnus}}<ref name = "WE">{{cite-web |title=Etymology in Webster's Unabridged Dictionary |url=http://machaut.uchicago.edu/?action=search&word=yean&resource=Webster%27s&quicksearch=on |accessdate=27 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619122315/http://machaut.uchicago.edu/?action=search&resource=Webster%27s&word=Yean&quicksearch=on |archivedate=19 June 2010 }}</ref>, {{cog|grc|ἀμνός}}<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/yean Etymology in Merriam-Webster's Dictionary]</ref>, {{cog|sga|úan||lamb}}<ref name ="WE"/>. See also {{m|en|ean}}. ===Verb=== {{en-verb}} # {{lb|en|transitive|archaic|of goats or sheep}} To give birth to. ===Quotations=== * {{seeCites|en}} ===References=== <references/> ===Anagrams=== * {{anagrams|en|a=aeny|Enya|ayen}}
